	<item>
				<title>Hawkesbury River 2011</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2011/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 31 Dec 2011 01:07:23 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://phwl.wordpress.com/?p=281</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Went with Warren to the Hawkesbury River for 3 days of fishing and camping.

<img class="alignnone" title="camp" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/PC284255.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

<!--more-->

Our boat is now 20 years old and starting to be looking a bit old and tired (I didn't know aluminium could rust). Before we could go, we had to do a few things including installing a new sounder, filling the holes from the old one and fixing the trailer.

<img class="alignnone" title="Car" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3807.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

This being the Christmas period, the boat ramp was absolutely packed with people, boats and pelicans.

<img title="Pelikan" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3852.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

The first job was to pump saltwater pink nippers from a nearby sandflat.

<img class="alignnone" title="Nipper pumping" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3854.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

(photo below from http://www.dreamfish.com.au/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=57:how-to-catch-nippers-saltwater-yabbies&amp;catid=34:fishing-articles&amp;Itemid=54)

<img class="alignnone" title="Nippers" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/yabby-08.gif" alt="" width="500" height="214" />

To get to the fishing location you pass by Milsons Passage. Nice place to have a holiday house but a bit inconvenient since you can only get there by boat. At any time, about half of them are for sale.

<img class="alignnone" title="Milson Island" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3858.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

Around the corner and you are in the middle of nowhere.

<img class="alignnone" title="Channel near Bar Pt" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3906.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

Caught a fish for dinner

<img class="alignnone" title="Bream" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3837.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

and then we had to find a camping spot, pitch our tents and get some firewood. Had steaks and pan fried bream for dinner.

<img class="alignnone" title="Tents" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3871.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

<img class="alignnone" title="Campsite" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3815.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

<img class="alignnone" title="Fire" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3819.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

Got out early the following morning. For the first few hours we didn't do very well but then got into some fish. The next hour was one of those times where you catch a fish every cast.

<img class="alignnone" title="Catch" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3842.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

I wish they wouldn't allow trawlers to fish the Hawkesbury.

<img class="alignnone" title="Trawler" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3902.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

For dinner, we had fresh fish and baked potatoes cooked on the coals.

<img class="alignnone" title="Camp fire" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3879.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

<img class="alignnone" title="Bream cooked with lemons in foil." src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3885.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

That evening we had a perfectly clear night. Part of the Orion constellation appears near the bottom of the photo.

<img class="alignnone" title="Stars" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/PC294266.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

This was a 1 minute exposure, taken on the beach at our campsite.

<img class="alignnone" title="Portrait" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/PC294265.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

Next day was a clear, sunny day. We knew where to go and got straight into more fish. Here is Warren hooked up.

<img class="alignnone" title="Warren hooked up" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3888.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

Another fish

<img title="Warren bream" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3863.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

Our fishing spot was also the runway for float planes.

<img class="alignnone" title="Float plane" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3865.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

By mid-morning we had enough in the keeper net and decided to call it a day.

<img class="alignnone" title="Keeper net" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3895.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

A crowded boat ramp at Mooney Mooney.

<img title="Mooney Mooney boat ramp" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3908.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

That was the end of a wonderful  fishing trip. Only thing left to do was to clean the day's catch, boat, outboard, rods, reels, cutlery, pots, ...

<img class="alignnone" title="Fish cleaning" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3909.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

<img class="alignnone" title="Fish" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/IMG_3911.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

Bream steamed with shallots and ginger.

<img class="alignnone" title="Cooked" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/P1110157.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="480" />

Here is a video of Warren landing a fish:

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Vvty1pfwl8Q

[gallery orderby="post_date"]]]></content:encoded>

It is very informative and well worth visiting <a title="http://www.linkysbeachdays.com/" href="http://www.linkysbeachdays.com/">http://www.linkysbeachdays.com/</a>.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Postcard from Shanghai</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/postcard-from-shanghai/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 19 Apr 2012 07:36:09 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://phwl.wordpress.com/?p=342</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[
Spent a fortnight over Easter in Shanghai,

<img class="alignnone" title="Shanghai street scene" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110707.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

<!--more-->

as a visitor at Fudan University

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110572.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

Played ping pong with students.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110573.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

Had a ride on the maglev to the airport. As one of the websites say, it is mainly for show since the ride is only 8 min. It is impressive though, goes up to 430 km/h, quite an experience.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110582.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/IMG_1315.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

This is the Oriental Pearl Tower which is 468m high

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110617.jpg" alt="" height="800" />

and the Bund from above

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110619.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

It has a transparent floor, very unsettling to walk on

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110633.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110636.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

Street vendor.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110736.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

Here people are paying to get beaten up.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110743.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

Cheng Huang Temple

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110773.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

We visited Chairman Mao’s former residence in Shanghai

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110832.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

He was quite a poet, as was his son.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110867.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

Self portrait.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110895.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

Juxtaposition of old and new.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110907.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

They have a wonderful canteen at Fudan. Here is part of the breakfast offering.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110567.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

Xiao long buns.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110805.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

Crab roe and vegetables.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110683.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

I saved the best for last, pig face jerky - quite a delicacy.

<img src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/P1110800.jpg" alt="" width="800" />

Thanks to the hospitality of my host, Professor Wang, and his students, particularly Mr Li and Mr Chen, I had a great time in Shanghai. This is the first opportunity I have had to explore this beautiful city. I look forward to my next visit.

[gallery orderby="post_date"]]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Molonglo Radio Observatory</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/molonglo-radio-observatory/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 11 Nov 2012 10:54:26 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/?p=345</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[The University of Sydney's <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molonglo_Observatory_Synthesis_Telescope">Molonglo Radio Observatory</a> is located about 3-4 hours south of Sydney. It is being used to prototype some of the technologies in the proposed <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_Kilometre_Array">Square Kilometer Array</a>.

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/P1120459-1024x768.jpg" alt="" />

<!--more-->

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/P1120454-1024x768.jpg" alt="" />

I visited the site to see whether the School of Electrical and Information Engineering, could strength its links with Molonglo. In the past, there was close collaboration with the School of Physics on radio astronomy.

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/P1120460-1024x768.jpg" alt="" />

The telescope consists of two arms, each about a kilometer in length and a cylindrical paraboloid in shape.

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/P1120459-1024x768.jpg" alt="" />

There is also a junior version.

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/P1120501-1024x768.jpg" alt="" />

Under the antennas are the amplifiers and ADCs.

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/P1120504-1024x768.jpg" alt="" />

Lots of equipment inside the Observatory.

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/P1120480-1024x768.jpg" alt="" />

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/P1120484-1024x768.jpg" alt="" />

This is the manager, Duncan Campbell-Wilson. He has a pet tiger snake but I didn't see it on my visit - maybe next time. Unfortunately, I didn't take a photo of his colleague, Darshan Thakkar who is doing most of the FPGA design work.

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/P1120490-1024x768.jpg" alt="" />

On my return trip, I met up with a friend I hadn't seen for about 20 years, fishing guru, Steve Samuels. We fishined Googong Dam and caught a few redfin, but nothing to write about.

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/DSC_5128-1024x681.jpg" alt="" />

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/DSC_5139-1024x681.jpg" alt="" />

Slept the night in my car around Pejar Dam. It was a new moon and being way away from the city, I had a magnificent view of the stars.

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/DSC_5147-1024x612.jpg" alt="" />

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/DSC_5151-1024x681.jpg" alt="" />

Morning fog.

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/P1120520-1024x768.jpg" alt="" />

<img src="http://mackereltechcom.ipage.com/phwl/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/DSC_5158-1024x681.jpg" alt="" />

<strong>Gallery</strong>

[gallery]]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>

		<wp:post_date_gmt>2012-11-11 10:54:26</wp:post_date_gmt>
		<wp:comment_status>open</wp:comment_status>
		<wp:ping_status>open</wp:ping_status>
		<wp:post_name>molonglo-radio-observatory</wp:post_name>

	</item>
	<item>
				<title>Hawkesbury River 2012</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 25 Dec 2012 00:32:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.phwl.org/blog/?p=495</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[In what has turned out to become an annual event (click on <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2011/">this link</a> for the 2011 version), went on a 4 day camping trip to the Hawkesbury River with my high-school friend, Warren. We camp on a beach which is only accessible by boat.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-22/" rel="attachment wp-att-516"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-516" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC210130-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

<!--more-->

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-24/" rel="attachment wp-att-518"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-518" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC220143-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

This year, someone had erected a very handy table.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-18/" rel="attachment wp-att-512"><img alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC220144-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

Oysters are available by our campsite.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-4/" rel="attachment wp-att-500"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-500" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230232-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

We saw this brush turkey at the boat ramp. I resisted the temptation of bagging it for Christmas dinner.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-21/" rel="attachment wp-att-515"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-515" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC210115-1024x766.jpg" width="584" height="436" /></a>

This year, we only had to share it with this monitor lizard which went through all our rubbish and also stole some of our fish.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-9/" rel="attachment wp-att-502"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-502" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230225-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-11/" rel="attachment wp-att-504"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-504" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230196-768x1024.jpg" width="584" height="778" /></a>

During the night, we saw this owl take a mouse from a few meters away.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-7/" rel="attachment wp-att-499"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-499" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230260-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

There were more jellyfish this year than we have ever seen. I didn't get a photo but one morning there were hundreds on the surface of the water.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-23/" rel="attachment wp-att-517"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-517" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC220140-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

Apart from the wildlife, we had some excellent fishing. Caught a shovel nose shark (but didn't take a photo) as well as several large stingrays from the beach. They stingrays put up a great fight.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-19/" rel="attachment wp-att-513"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-513" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC220150-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-15/" rel="attachment wp-att-508"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-508" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC220168-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

We released the largest flathead.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-17/" rel="attachment wp-att-511"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-511" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230176-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-12/" rel="attachment wp-att-505"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-505" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230186-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

as well as this tailor.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-5/" rel="attachment wp-att-497"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-497" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230254-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

This jewfish, however, was barbecued.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-6/" rel="attachment wp-att-498"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-498" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230258-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

Keeper net keeps the fish alive while we are fishing.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-16/" rel="attachment wp-att-509"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-509" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230172-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

A couple of beam for lunch.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-10/" rel="attachment wp-att-503"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-503" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230201-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

A non-seafood dinner with T-bone steaks, onions, and sweet corn wrapped in foil.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-20/" rel="attachment wp-att-514"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-514" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC220153-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

I had another wonderful trip, and the Hawkesbury River is only 30 min from home. However, this fisherman was unloading bream from a fish trap, and trawlers go through the area every day. This leaves me to wonder whether commercial fishing in the area is absolutely necessary. Banning of commercial fishing as they have done in Sydney Harbour, would certainly result in improved fish stocks and ensure the long term sustainability of this special place.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/hawkesbury-river-2012-2/olympus-digital-camera-13/" rel="attachment wp-att-506"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-506" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/PC230189-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

&nbsp;

[gallery ids="515,518,517,516,514,513,512,511,509,508,507,506,505,519,504,503,502,501,500,499,498,497"]

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

	<item>
				<title>Lake Eucumbene 2013</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/lake-eucumbene-2013/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 08 Jan 2013 07:36:51 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.phwl.org/blog/?p=533</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Lake Eucumbene is an alpine lake about 500km south west of Sydney. My fishing mate, Beard (nickname which refered to his facial hair - he doesn't have one anymore but the name stuck), and I made a trip down there to fish with former fly-fishing guide and Eucumbene guru, Steve.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/lake-eucumbene-2013/p1130242/" rel="attachment wp-att-537"><img alt="P1130242" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/P1130242-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

<!--more-->

We camped at Buckenderra Holiday Village, situated at the bottom end of the lake. According to Steve, fishing has been exceptional in the last few years because new ground was flooded every year. Unfortunately, when we were there, the lake was low and weather conditions extremely hot (35 degrees celsius, 95 fahrenheit). Fishing was not good and no fish were caught the night before.
<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/lake-eucumbene-2013/olympus-digital-camera-26/" rel="attachment wp-att-534"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-534" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/P1040398-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/lake-eucumbene-2013/olympus-digital-camera-32/" rel="attachment wp-att-542"><img alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/P1040387-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

The first evening saw us fishing in a location only accessible by 4 wheel drive. We had 6 anglers (myself, Beard, Steve and 3 of Steve's friends) in two cars. Conditions seemed good as it was hot and humid, with lots of bugs hatching, particularly midges. Lots of dragonfly nymph shells could be found on the shore. In fact, they were so good I wished that I had not left the insect repellant in the car.

Here is a photo of Steve fishing at sunset.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/lake-eucumbene-2013/olympus-digital-camera-28/" rel="attachment wp-att-538"><img alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/P1040414-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

I was fishing an Alexandra (shown below) because it is a beautiful fly and has a history. It was invented in 1860 and originally called the "Lady of the Lake". It was later renamed in honour of Princess Alexandra of Denmark who married Edward VII in 1863. In the old days, it was so effective that there was talk of banning this fly.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/lake-eucumbene-2013/olympus-digital-camera-30/" rel="attachment wp-att-540"><img alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/P1050458-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

All evening, I was fishing badly, catching my fly on nearly every object in front and behind. The fishing was tough with very few fish rising, and those that did were well outside fly-casting range.

After a long period of time, a trout rose directly in front of me and I was able to cover it with a cast. I started a slow retrieve (which is very difficult to do when a fish is nearby). It took the fly and the rod buckled over. The fish then promptly wrapped my 4lb tippet around a nearby snag protruding from the water. I was able to wade out to it and, using my feet, lift the unlucky trout out of the water and bring it back to shore.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/lake-eucumbene-2013/olympus-digital-camera-29/" rel="attachment wp-att-539"><img alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/P1040429-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

It was a reasonably nice rainbow trout, and had a clipped fin. It was autopsied and we found it to not be particularly fully, and its diet to have been midge pupae. We were later able to identify the fish as being a 4 year old from its fin as they clip the right and left pectoral and dorsal fins according to year. Shortly after catching my fish, Steve got a similar sized wild rainbow, which had midge pupae and a bloodworm in its stomach. Then the fishing shut down and no more fish were caught, as it turns out, for the rest of the trip.

The next morning we were up at 5:30am to fish Middlingbank. Fished all morning without seeing a single rise. Two guys in a boat were catching some fish trolling though.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/lake-eucumbene-2013/olympus-digital-camera-31/" rel="attachment wp-att-541"><img alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/P1050491-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

Here is a photograph of Beard casting.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/lake-eucumbene-2013/olympus-digital-camera-33/" rel="attachment wp-att-543"><img alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/P1040400-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

The following morning, we went out in Steve's boat. This was a real treat for us and it is a beautiful bass boat which was imported from the US and not very common in Australia. Although we tried a number of really good looking spots, the only thing that happened in 4 hours of fishing was that a trout took and spat out my fly while I was fiddling with my camera.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/lake-eucumbene-2013/olympus-digital-camera-27/" rel="attachment wp-att-535"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-535" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/P1060529-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

Although we were hoping to do better than a single fish in three solid days of fishing, we were rather lucky to catch any at all given the difficult conditions. Lake Eucumbene is a beautiful and tranquil place, and I hope to return soon. It is particularly special to me as I caught my first trout on fly here under Steve's guidance 20 years ago.]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Postcard from Harbin</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/postcard-from-harbin/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 25 Feb 2013 13:33:21 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.phwl.org/blog/?p=851</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Had a really cool time in Harbin.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241417.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-879" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241417.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

&nbsp;

<!--more-->

This was the view from my departing flight,<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2180977.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-852" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2180977.jpg" width="1280" height="660" /></a>

and this was the view arriving in Harbin. <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2221072.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-853" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2221072.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2221087.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-854" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2221087.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Needless to say, they are very different cities.

My hosts, Prof Yu Peng and Dr Shaojun Wang kindly arranged for Basin Wang and Rigui Yi, both postgraduate students at Harbin Institute of Technology to take me out on fantastic Lantern Festival day. They were very nice to me, despite being forced to listen to 8 hours of my lectures.

We first visited the <a href="http://www.dongbeihu.net.cn/">Siberia Tiger Park</a> which was amazing, particularly since Siberian Tigers are a seriously endangered species. We took a bus ride through the park, from which we could get really close to the animals.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240486.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-855" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240486.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

While most of them were reddish-yellow in color, we saw a couple of white ones.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241126.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-870" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241126.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

After the bus ride, we walked around a caged area.
<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241261.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-871" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241261.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

This keeper was preparing live chickens for feeding.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241314.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-872" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241314.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

I know that the tigers are thinking, "it's KFC time". I wonder what the chicken is thinking?

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241362n.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-917" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241362n.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

We had lunch at Longhua Yucun Restaurant.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241386.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-876" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241386.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

These were just kept as pets and not on the menu.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241409.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-878" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241409.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

A really large wok.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241396.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-877" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241396.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

This photo is with Haomiao Wang and Rigui Yi. The tables in this restaurant were designed like boats. I am thinking of redecorating our kitchen in the same style. <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241373.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-874" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241373.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

This is the Songhua River. There is a sign which says "No swimming". I strongly doubt you could do that even if you wanted to.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240502.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-857" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240502.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Next we visited the <em>Harbin Sun Island</em> International Snow Sculpture Art Expo, where there were snow sculptures on display. It is a very lovely park and some of the sculptures were really impressive. The best way to describe it to Sydneysiders is that it is sort of like <a href="http://www.sculpturebythesea.com/">Sculpture by the Sea</a>, except it is really cold and there is no sea even though it is on an island.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240510.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-858" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240510.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a> <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240532.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-859" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240532.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

This one is Beethoven.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240536.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-860" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240536.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

The Songhua River with Harbin in the background.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240537.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-861" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240537.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Of course, the main attraction is the Harbin Snow and Ice Festival.
<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241417.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-879" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241417.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>
<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240567.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-862" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240567.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a> <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240585.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-864" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240585.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

It wasn't long before the temperature dropped to -20 C.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240580.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-863" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240580.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

This is the "Angry birds" area.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240594.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-865" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240594.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a><a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240617.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-867" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240617.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

I was very impressed by the display.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240607.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-866" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240607.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a> <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240624.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-868" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240624.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Just as were were about to leave, they put on some Lantern Day fireworks.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240708.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-869" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2240708.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Following dinner at the Boteman Xi Canting Restaurant where we had Russian food, we walked to the Songhua River where people were sending up hot air balloons fueled with candles.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2251571.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-881" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2251571.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

All the orange dots in the air are lanterns. It was a very beautiful sight and I wish I was able to get a better photo. <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241539.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-880" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2241539.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

I was so tired the following day, I didn't feel like playing tennis.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2251590.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-907" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2251590.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

This is the student canteen. They have food from many different provinces. The food is good and very inexpensive.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2251591.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-908" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2251591.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

For example a fried sauce noodle zhajiangmian with spring onion pancake costs 8 RMB.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2251593.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-909" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2251593.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

I had a fantastic time due to the wonderful hospitality of my hosts, Prof Yu Peng, Dr Shaojun Wang, Dr Liu Datong, Yeyong Pang and Jianbo Zhou.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2281619.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-925" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2281619.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Profs Qian-fan Zhang and Liguo Wang.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2261602.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-928" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2261602.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

I was treated to some wonderful meals as can be seen below.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2157.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-922" alt="IMG_2157" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2157.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2152.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-926" alt="IMG_2152" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2152.jpg" width="960" height="1280" /></a> <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2153.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-927" alt="IMG_2153" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2153.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>
<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2166.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-923" alt="IMG_2166" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2166.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2281623.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-931" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P2281623.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a> <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2144.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-932" alt="IMG_2144" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2144.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a> <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2145.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-933" alt="IMG_2145" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2145.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a> <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2146.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-934" alt="IMG_2146" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2146.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Things went pear-shaped on my return journey. Heavy snow was forecast for just after my departure and, of course, my flight was delayed. The snow fell so hard I couldn't see the planes from inside the terminal. Amazingly, the runway was operational about 10 minutes after the snow stopped, and there was still hope to make the flight. Our China Southern plane then had some other mechanical problem and we arrived in Shanghai and hour after my Qantas flight had departed. This was the first time I had ever missed a connection.

The guy at the gate didn't particularly want to help me, and I was hot under the collar because: (1)  I was tired and (2) the long underwear I was still wearing as not appropriate for Shanghai. I tried to put pressure on him by writing down his name, Shi Xi Sheng. When I got to the ticketing counter I noticed the girl there had the same name! Guess they got a bulk deal on those name tags. Since Qantas was closed for the day, all they could do is arrange a hotel room.  I later found out the name means "occupational trainee".

To cut a long story short, I did manage to get the last seat on the flight back to Sydney the next day, which, incidentally was filled with students returning for first semester. The person sitting behind me knew me as he was a student in our School. Anyway, the extra day in Shanghai wasn't a total loss, I was able to have crab roe xiao long bao.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2175.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-924" alt="IMG_2175" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/IMG_2175.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

&nbsp;

I'll finish with a travel tip for those not terribly familiar with China. Most hotels have free wired ethernet but no wifi. If you bring something like this <a href="http://www.tp-link.com.au/products/details/?model=TL-MR3020">TP-Link TL-MR3020 Wireless N Router</a>, you can turn it into a wifi hotspot and connect your phone etc. This is particularly useful if you either don't bring a laptop or, like me, have a machine with no ethernet.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P3011632.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-946" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/P3011632.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Went for a drive this morning to Akuna Bay. Fog was coming off the river and this photograph was taken on the road between Akuna Bay and Church Point.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/akunabay.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-956" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/akunabay.jpg" width="1280" height="609" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Shanghai April 2013</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/shanghai-april-2013/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 30 Apr 2013 11:27:14 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.phwl.org/blog/?p=961</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[I had an excellent trip to Shanghai last year and wrote about it in  <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/postcard-from-shanghai/">http://www.phwl.org/blog/postcard-from-shanghai/</a>. I was fortunate enough to be invited back.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242220.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-993" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242220.jpg" width="3533" height="2650" /></a>

<!--more-->

I stayed in the Expert building, Zhangjiang Campus.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/IMG_2402.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-995" alt="IMG_2402" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/IMG_2402.jpg" width="3264" height="2448" /></a>

This is the library.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4232072.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-977" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4232072.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

There were many highlights to this visit. Chen Shuai kindly accompanied me to visit the former residence of Soong Ching Ling, Sun Yat-sen's wife (we also went to Sun Yat-sen's former residence but that was not as interesting).

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4211923.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-970" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4211923.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a><a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P42119151.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-969" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P42119151.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

Soong Ching Ling was someone I greatly admire, She had friends like Stalin, who gave her this car.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4211938.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-971" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4211938.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

This was one of her favourite books.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4211930.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-999" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4211930.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

Here is one of her poems.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/II.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-994" alt="II" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/II.jpg" width="2448" height="3264" /></a>

I also went to the China Pavilion at the World Expo Site.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4212031.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-975" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4212031.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

This was a very impressive giant moving display of village life.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4212009.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-974" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4212009.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

We went to little supermarkets,

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P42119131.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-968" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P42119131.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

and a huge mall

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4212063.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-976" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4212063.jpg" width="2736" height="3648" /></a>

This time, I also had an opportunity to visit the main campus of Fudan University.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242092.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-978" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242092.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

At 30 storeys, this is the tallest university building in Asia. We went there for coffee.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242100.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-979" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242100.jpg" width="2304" height="3072" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242125.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-981" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242125.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242189.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-987" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242189.jpg" width="3415" height="2561" /></a><a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242193.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-988" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242193.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

This is the canteen.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242162.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-983" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242162.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a><a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242168.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-985" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242168.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a><a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242167.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-984" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4242167.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

Back to Sydney.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4272248.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-996" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/P4272248.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>High Altitude Balloon Launch #1</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/high-altitude-balloon-launch-1/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 23 May 2013 13:21:52 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.phwl.org/blog/?p=1026</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Our <a href="http://www.ee.usyd.edu.au">Sydney University Electrical Engineering </a>students, Stephen Tridgell and David Portelli successfully made a high-altitude balloon launch from Blayney, NSW. Stephen's report is after the jump.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/GOPR5590.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1030" alt="DCIM101GOPRO" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/GOPR5590.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

<!--more-->

Excellent job guys!

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/936768_10200551479541477_289143142_n.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1042" alt="936768_10200551479541477_289143142_n" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/936768_10200551479541477_289143142_n.jpg" width="960" height="720" /></a>

<!--more-->

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/942112_10200551489181718_819025503_n.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1028" alt="942112_10200551489181718_819025503_n" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/942112_10200551489181718_819025503_n.jpg" width="960" height="720" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/GOPR4668.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1029" alt="DCIM100GOPRO" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/GOPR4668.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/GOPR4935.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1029" alt="DCIM100GOPRO" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/GOPR4935.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/GOPR5590.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1030" alt="DCIM101GOPRO" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/GOPR5590.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/942273_10200551505942137_1613835602_n.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1043" alt="942273_10200551505942137_1613835602_n" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/942273_10200551505942137_1613835602_n.jpg" width="960" height="720" /></a>

&nbsp;

<strong>Balloon Launch Report (by Stephen Tridgell)</strong>

On the 11th of May a Balloon with approximately a 2Kg payload was launched from Blayney Tourist Park. The balloon contained:
<ul>
	<li>A Find Me Spot GPS Tracker</li>
	<li>A HTC smart phone</li>
	<li>A Go Pro 2 Camera</li>
	<li>An Arduino Uno board</li>
	<li>A high current output stage</li>
	<li>Nichrome wire</li>
	<li>A Radar Reflector constructed of aluminium foil and cardboard</li>
	<li>A Small parachute</li>
	<li>A Medipack Heat warmer</li>
</ul>
<strong>Regulations:</strong>

In order to meet CASA approval we were required to have the following:
<ul>
	<li>A method of popping the balloon from the ground</li>
	<li>A suitable launch site far away from any flight paths</li>
	<li>That it be fitted with a radar reflector</li>
	<li>That the personnel launching the balloon must be contactable during its flight</li>
</ul>
<strong>Design of the Balloon:</strong>

To meet these requirements a radar reflector was constructed out of aluminum foil and cardboard. The chosen method of popping the balloon was to use nichrome wire around the balloons neck and if necessary heat up the wire by putting a large current through it to melt the neck of the balloon. In order to achieve this an Arduino Board was used with a output stage capable of drawing large current. The Arduino board would be triggered via bluetooth from the HTC phone when it received a message. There would also be an independent GPS tracker and a Camera to take scenic photos.

<strong>Construction of the Balloon System:</strong>

The balloon was constructed over a few weeks which was mostly focused on enclosing all the items securely in a box. The chosen method for this was to drill holes in the box and tie down the components with cable ties. A small piece of plywood was also used to secure the Go Pro camera to the box. It was theorized that the box would get quite cold when the balloon achieved sufficient altitude. To attempt to combat this, a heat Medipack was attached to the lid of the box. In order for the box to be successfully communicated with a python Script was developed to run on the HTC phone with a corresponding Bluetooth program running on the Arduino Uno. On the Uno it was necessary to use four digital pins in order to sink sufficient current into the board so that the current over the Nichrome wire would be high enough to pop the balloon. There was some experimentation and it was found that the wire required around 2 to 2.5 Amps to heat up enough to pop the balloon. Fishing line was selected as the means of holding the box, parachute, radar reflector and balloon together as it is high strength. There was a limited amount that could be done until right before the launch as all the components in the box were battery powered and hence could not be securely fastened until they had been activated.

<strong>Issues before the Launch:</strong>

The launch team arrived at the site a 1pm, which was about an hour later than expected. Setting up all the equipment ready for launch also took longer than expected resulting in a launch at around 15:30.  One issue was that many things needed to be done just before the launch such as:
<ul>
	<li>GPS set up to Track</li>
	<li>Aduino Uno On and connected to the output Stage</li>
	<li>Phone on and Connected via Bluetooth to the Uno</li>
	<li>Go Pro Camera set to take Photos every 2 Secs</li>
	<li>Medi Heat Pack activated</li>
	<li>Sealing the box</li>
	<li>Filling up the balloon with helium</li>
</ul>
Additionally, the first time the balloon wasn't filled up enough resulting in a very anti-climatic launch. The balloon had to be detached, filled a little more and reattached to the payload. For this payload the balloon required 3.5 m^3 of helium at 1atm.

<strong>Issues After Launch:</strong>

Immediately after launch the balloon was observed to be swinging the payload rather vigorously.  Fortunately the payload was securely fastened and the fishing line did not break. The balloon was tracked visually initially and was heading south. The first GPS tracking point confirmed this, however after the tracking point at 15:40 the GPS did not send a tracking point until 16:40 which was at its final resting place. The loss of GPS means we cannot map its trajectory which was a little disappointing. From the camera evidence it can be gathered that it took approximately 40 minutes to reach the peak after launch and 20 minutes to come back down. The first image after launch was judged to be at around 20m, This implies an initial vertical velocity of around 10m/s. Extrapolating this to the average speed of the upwards flight this implies it reached a maximum height of 79 000 feet. This is consistent with the images obtained as a height of around this is necessary to see the curvature of the earth. As it took only 20 minutes to come down, it was calculated that the balloon probably hit the ground at 70-75 km/hour. This is a lot faster than expected and is possibly due to the parachute getting tangled on the way down. The likely reason for this appears to be the balloon which, after popping was still attached to the rest of the balloon. The speed at which it came down is an issue that needs to be improved upon in future launches as it could cause significant damage. There will have to be design improvements and possibly a larger parachute or a smaller payload.

<strong>Issues with the Recovery:</strong>

As the balloon was launched late, the recovery started late too. The prediction had showed a position far to the east, thus after launch the team made their way to Bathurst. The first point at the landing sight was detected at 16:40 however it was mistakenly hypothesized that this was simply a point while it was still in the air as the predicted flight time was a lot longer than an hour and a lot further. When it was eventually realized there were several scattered GPS locations and the team made their way to the landing site. They reached it at around 18:00, after dark. The numerous GPS positions meant that there was a reasonable area that it could have landed in and the landing site, though near a dirt road had a few barbed wire fences and other obstacles. The balloon was not found the night it landed, due to uncertainty in the accuracy of the GPS and lack of light. In order for it to be found more easily in the future, it is recommended that the balloon be fitted with a buzzer and a flashing light. This would enable it to be more reliably and quickly recovered. It was found the next day to be very close to a few of the GPS points so it is believed that the accuracy is fairly good but there were a few points on the map far from where it was found. It can be seen from the landing site and the picture prior to landing that the balloon hit a tree and came to rest on the ground.

<strong>Summary:</strong>

The launch was a success as the balloon reached a high altitude took fantastic pictures and was recovered successfully. There were a few areas for improvement as there could have been issues with the launch. The highest priority one is a larger or better parachute deployment as it came down far too fast, which could not only damage the equipment but could harm someone or a third parties property. The launch timing needed to be planned better so that it could be recovered before dark. Possibly a more accurate GPS or one that could work at higher altitude.

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Kangaroo Tagging at Nelson Bay</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/kangaroo-tagging-at-nelson-bay/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 11 Jul 2013 02:26:34 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.phwl.org/blog/?p=1064</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[I had the opportunity to visit the Nelson Bay Golf Course and observe the tagging programme of semi-wild Eastern Grey Kangaroos being conducted by a colleague in Veterinary Science. Our interest in this work is to later measure the dietary intake of a number of these kangaroos using Android phones.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090917.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1065" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090917.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

The kangaroos are digging up the golf course and we are also trying to understand why they are doing so.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090851.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1078" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090851.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

They are first tranquillised by walking up to them and jabbing them with one of these. A dart gun will probably need to be used for some of the more cautious ones.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090883.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1075" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090883.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Here is one of the tags.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092773.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1067" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092773.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

The kangaroos being measured.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092734.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1074" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092734.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

We are going to fit a collar like the one below when we do our study.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092741.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1072" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092741.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

Here we are checking whether a mobile phone would fit around its neck comfortably.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092744.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1070" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092744.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

The joey being measured.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092758.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1066" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092758.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Blood sample.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092752.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1068" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092752.jpg" width="3648" height="2736" /></a>

Tagging.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090901.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1073" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090901.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

This one weighed about 65 kg.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092748.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1069" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092748.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Tagged kangaroo.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092747.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1071" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7092747.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Release.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090886.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1076" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090886.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>

Tagged kangaroo back on the golf course.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090857.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1079" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/P7090857.jpg" width="1280" height="960" /></a>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Cowan Creek</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/cowan-creek/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 30 Jul 2013 07:30:20 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.phwl.org/blog/?p=1088</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Photos from a short trip to Cowan Creek on a foggy morning. More after the jump.

				<title>Panorama of Sydney Opera House and the Harbour Bridge</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/panorama-of-sydney-opera-house-and-the-harbour-bridge/</link>

		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>

	<item>
				<title>Postcard from Harbin Summer 2013</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/postcard-from-harbin-summer-2013/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 22 Aug 2013 12:57:58 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.phwl.org/blog/?p=1120</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[After a superb trip to <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/postcard-from-harbin/">Harbin in winter</a>, I returned in summer to attend the ICEMI conference, kindly hosted again by Prof Peng Yu, Prof Shaojun Wang and Mr Yeyong Pang from Harbin Institute of Technology.

This is the view from Dragon Tower.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8193616.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1145" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8193616-1024x270.jpg" width="584" height="153" /></a>

and an 11MB, 30-shot 360 degree panorama of Harbin.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/harbin-pano3.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1160" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/harbin-pano3-1024x94.jpg" width="584" height="53" /></a><!--more-->

The difference could not be greater. In February, the Songhua River where the guy below is swimming was frozen solid.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8152916.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1132" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8152916-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

Sun Island is where they had the International Snow Sculpture Art Festival. We fed the fish.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8152975.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1133" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8152975-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

As well as the deer.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8153140.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1131" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8153140-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

View from behind a waterfall.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8153123.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1134" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8153123-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

Songhua River at Sun Island.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8153164.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1130" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8153164-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

Siberian Tiger Park.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8183278.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1126" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8183278-1024x767.jpg" width="584" height="437" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8183366.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1127" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8183366-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

Here are some shop workers doing a dance before work. In the background you can see both Chinese and Russian signs, unique to Harbin.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8163181.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1129" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8163181-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

This photo shows a number of contrasts between old and new.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8193595.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1128" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8193595-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

People burning stuff for good luck during the Hungry Ghost Festival.<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8203759.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1124" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8203759-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

We then took a long trip (about 6 hours by car each direction) to Jinpo Lake, and walked through the Underground Forest which is at the bottom of a volcano crater. <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8213813.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1123" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8213813-768x1024.jpg" width="584" height="778" /></a>

Diaoshuilou Falls. According to the sign, it is "the world's largest lava air-hole collapse-type waterfall" (whatever that means). Anyway, it was spectcular. <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8223887.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1122" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8223887-1024x404.jpg" width="584" height="230" /></a>

I was also impressed by the beauty of the countryside. Here is a photo taken from the car. The crops in the foreground are rice and corn.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8223939.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1136" alt="OLYMPUS DIGITAL CAMERA" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/P8223939-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

I had a wonderful trip due to the hospitality of my hosts. They will be visiting Sydney in October, and I hope that we can make their visit as enjoyable as mine.

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/panorama-of-the-gap/</link>

	<item>
				<title>Sydney University Open Day (from a weather balloon)</title>
		<link>http://www.phwl.org/blog/sydney-university-open-day-from-a-weather-balloon/</link>
		<pubDate>Sat, 31 Aug 2013 06:15:25 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[phwl]]></dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.phwl.org/blog/?p=1165</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[A photograph of the Sydney University Open Day from a weather balloon above the tower of the main quadrangle. This photo was made with <a href="http://www.ee.usyd.edu.au">Sydney University Electrical and Information Engineering </a>students Stephen Tridgell and David Portelli using the same equipment as our <a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/high-altitude-balloon-launch-1/">High Altitude Balloon project</a>.

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/GOPR7612.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1168" alt="DCIM100GOPRO" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/GOPR7612-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

<!--more-->
<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/GOPR7063.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1172" alt="DCIM100GOPRO" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/GOPR7063-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/GOPR7319.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1173" alt="DCIM100GOPRO" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/GOPR7319-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/GOPR7374.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1175" alt="DCIM100GOPRO" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/08/GOPR7374-1024x768.jpg" width="584" height="438" /></a>

<a href="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/hbridge-pano.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-1185" alt="Sydney Harbour Panorama" src="http://www.phwl.org/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/09/hbridge-pano-1024x382.jpg" width="584" height="217" /></a>]]></content:encoded>
